Key Insights & Analysis

  • Health Impact: Average of 5.5 estimated respiratory cases per day
  • Pollution Levels: PM2.5 average of 55.2 µg/m³ (exceeds WHO guidelines)
  • Primary Correlate: PM10 (ug/m3) shows strongest correlation (r = 0.160)
  • Data Quality: 100.0% complete

Key Characteristics

  • State leader in respiratory diseases (highest in India)
  • Severe healthcare bed shortage (76% gap)
  • Desert climate challenges (dust, temperature extremes)
  • Jaipur demonstrates how desert urbanization + infrastructure gaps create India's highest chronic lung disease burden
    •

    *Synthetic Data Considerations

  • Population: ~4.4 million (metro 2025); literacy 83.33%; sex ratio 900/1000; predominantly Hindu
  • Respiratory Disease: High burden—Rajasthan leads India in chronic lung disease (15% elderly); Asthma ~2%, COPD ~2%, bronchial asthma ~4%; state has highest asthma prevalence (12% among 60+)
  • Healthcare: Major hospitals include SMS (6,251 beds), Santokba Durlabhji (551 beds), multiple specialty centers; significant infrastructure gap—needs 397,512 beds but has only 93,176
  • Seasonal Patterns: Limited specific data; likely follows regional winter peak patterns for respiratory illnesses
  • Socioeconomic: State capital driving economic growth; GSDP rose from ₹10.17 lakh crore (2020-21) to ₹15.28 lakh crore (2023-24); targeting $350 billion economy by 2030
